<html xmlns:t="http://tapestry.apache.org/schema/tapestry_5_3.xsd">
<head>
    <style type="text/css">
        body				{ font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; }
        .required-field		{ border-right-color: orange; }
        .error-label		{ color: red; }
        .error-field		{ border-color: red; }
        .error-msg			{ color: red; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>No Validation Bubbles (1)</h1>

To display client-side validation errors without the bubbles, JumpStart provides 2 components: CustomForm and CustomError.<br/>
You simply use CustomForm instead of Form and you put CustomError where you want a field's error message to appear.<br/><br/>

<form t:type="CustomForm" t:id="names">
    <t:errors/>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <td><t:label for="firstName"/>:</td>
            <td><input t:type="TextField" t:id="firstName" t:validate="required, maxlength=10, letters" size="10"/></td>
            <td>(required, maxLength=10, letters only)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td></td>
            <td colspan="2"><t:CustomError for="firstName"/>Should be Here</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><t:label for="lastName"/>:</td>
            <td><input t:type="TextField" t:id="lastName" t:validate="required, maxLength=10, letters" size="10"/></td>
            <td>(required, maxLength=10, letters only)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td></td>
            <td colspan="2"><t:CustomError for="lastName"/></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td></td>
            <td colspan="2"><input type="submit" value="Display"/></td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</form><br/>

The components add and remove various CSS classes which you can use to control the appearance.<br/>

4 CSS classes are automatically added when a field is "required":
<ul>
    <li><strong>required-field</strong> is added to the field and <strong>required-field-c</strong> to its containing element.</li>
    <li><strong>required-label</strong> is added to the label and <strong>required-label-c</strong> to its containing element.</li>
</ul>
6 CSS classes are automatically added when a field is in error:
<ul>
    <li><strong>error-field</strong> is added to the field and <strong>error-field-c</strong> to its containing element.</li>
    <li><strong>error-label</strong> is added to the label and <strong>error-label-c</strong> to its containing element.</li>
    <li><strong>error-msg</strong> is added to the span generated by CustomError and <strong>error-msg-c</strong> to its containing element.</li>
</ul>
1 CSS class is always present when a CustomError has been used:
<ul>
    <li><strong>msg</strong> is always added to the span generated by CustomError.</li>
</ul>

In case you're wondering, here is how CustomForm and CustomError work:
<ul>
    <li><strong>CustomForm</strong> wraps a Form so it can introduce CustomValidationDecorator in place of the default decorator.</li>
    <li><strong>CustomValidationDecorator</strong> decorates fields and labels according to whether the field is "required" or has a
        server-side validation error.</li>
    <li><strong>CustomError</strong> generates an empty span element and adds javascript CustomError.js.</li>
    <li><strong>CustomError.js</strong> places and removes client-side validation errors.</li>
</ul>

